{
  "texts": [
    "Ritvo et al. [47] highlighted that women showed a higher rate of participation in CRC screening compared to men in several studies, although factors such as the type of screening test, participant risk group, and age could influence this trend.",
    "Moreover, higher educational attainment is associated with increased adherence to cervical and CRC screening [39], suggesting that educational level may play a role in screening compliance among women.Future work should include an expanded list of stressful life events by including a validated scale of stressful life events for patients from historically marginalized groups.",
    "Current EHR systems typically lack features for systematic representation and screening for stressful life events [48]; however, we anticipate that standards-setting initiatives such as United States Core Data for Interoperability (USCDI) and the Gravity Project initiative [49,50] may address these gaps.",
    "Studies have shown that interventions, such as patient navigation aimed at increasing adherence to CRC screening, can be effective [51].",
    "A more systematic and structured assessment of stressful life events may increase the range of interventions for people following stressful life events.At the same time, it is worth noting that no list of stressful life events is complete."
  ]
}